The twenty-ninth week of Trump\'92s second term was not defined by a single shock, but by the sense that the walls of neutral governance were closing in from many sides at once. Executive orders, agency directives, and targeted appointments reached into trade, health, immigration, higher education, and grantmaking, all with a common aim: to pull more levers of power inside the president\'92s direct reach and to bend institutions that once stood at arm\'92s length. At the same time, the tools of law and security were turned more openly toward political ends, while universities, data agencies, and archives found their independence narrowed. It was a week in which the Civic Covenant\'97the basic understanding that power would be exercised with restraint and in good faith\'97showed deep cracks across every dimension, even as the formal machinery of democracy continued to turn.\
\
On the Democracy Clock, Week 28 closed at 7:57 p.m., already late in the civic day. Week 29 ends at the same time, 7:57 p.m., with no net movement in minutes. The stillness of the hands does not mean nothing changed. It means that the week\'92s many shifts, taken together, did not yet cross the threshold into a new, more dangerous hour. Instead, they deepened patterns already present: executive power operating with thin oversight, law used more as a weapon than a limit, security forces aligned with political preservation, and agencies captured by private and ideological interests. Against this, there were pockets of resistance\'97a federal judge halting construction at an Everglades detention complex, lawmakers reintroducing voting-rights protections, state legislators fleeing to block gerrymanders, and congressional subpoenas seeking Epstein records. These counter-moves did not reverse the direction of travel, but they helped explain why the clock, for this week, held where it was.\
\
The clearest breach of the moral floor of truthfulness came in the assault on independent economic data. After the Bureau of Labor Statistics reported weak job growth and downward revisions, President Trump fired Erika McEntarfer, the commissioner of labor statistics, and then reinforced the move with public claims that the bureau was rigged against him. Multiple accounts describe the dismissal as punishment for unfavorable numbers, not misconduct. At the same time, he and his allies attacked the integrity of the jobs reports themselves, claiming they were manipulated to favor Democrats, even as economists explained that revisions were routine. This was not a symbolic quarrel over messaging. The BLS anchors the numbers used by the Federal Reserve, Congress, and the public to judge the economy. When its leadership is removed for telling the truth, and its data are smeared as partisan, the ground under democratic decision-making shifts. Economic data become another field of contest, to be massaged or ignored when they clash with the leader\'92s story.\
\
The firing did not stand alone. Trump publicly pressured Federal Reserve Chair Jerome Powell to resign for not cutting interest rates as he wished, even though he lacked legal authority to remove him without cause. The combination of personal attacks on the Fed and the purge at BLS signaled a broader willingness to politicize the institutions that manage money and measure its effects. At the same time, the administration pushed forward with new tariffs on dozens of countries, and a fresh wave of import taxes on more than sixty nations took effect. These measures, framed as strength and fairness, raised average tariff rates to levels not seen in nearly a century, driving up consumer prices and slowing growth in sectors already under strain. The spending bill that cut food assistance for 22.3 million families while preserving tax cuts for the wealthy showed where the burdens would fall. Inequality was not an accident of these choices; it was their function.\
\
Crony capitalism threaded through the week\'92s economic decisions. Medicare rules on expensive skin substitutes, designed under the previous administration to curb billions in spending on products with little scientific backing, were delayed and then rewritten after a $5 million donation from a key manufacturer to Trump\'92s super PAC. The new proposal capped payments but did not limit coverage to proven treatments, allowing companies like Extremity Care to keep billing Medicare at high rates. In parallel, the HONEST Act, a stock-trading ban for top officials, was timed so that its divestment requirements would not apply to Trump during his current term. Policy and ethics law were thus shaped to protect the president\'92s financial interests and those of major donors, even as food aid was cut and tariffs squeezed household budgets. The moral floor of stewardship\'97care for public resources and the vulnerable\'97was breached in plain view.\
\
If economic data were bent, universities and knowledge institutions were pressed even harder. Brown University secured the restoration of frozen federal funds only by agreeing to adopt the administration\'92s narrow definitions of male and female, a change advocates warned would harm transgender students and staff. Columbia University settled antisemitism claims by paying over $220 million, accepting an independent monitor, revising its Middle East curriculum, and adopting a definition of antisemitism that conflates criticism of Israel with hatred of Jews. UCLA, despite paying $6 million to settle a lawsuit over its handling of pro-Palestinian protests, saw more than $300 million in federal funding frozen on grounds of \'93antisemitism and bias.\'94 Harvard went the other way, filing lawsuits to challenge $2.6 billion in funding cuts and the loss of its ability to host international students, winning some early victories but facing ongoing pressure to conform. Taken together, these actions turned federal money into a lever for ideological control, signaling to universities that their autonomy, curricula, and admissions policies would be judged not by academic standards but by alignment with the administration\'92s views.\
\
The pressure extended into admissions. An executive action and accompanying memo ordered colleges and universities to submit detailed data proving that race plays no role in admissions decisions, going beyond the Supreme Court\'92s 2023 ruling against affirmative action. Education Secretary Linda McMahon was directed to overhaul federal higher-education databases to support this scrutiny. On paper, the move was framed as enforcing non-discrimination. In practice, it threatened to chill efforts to maintain diverse student bodies and to turn statistical reporting into a tool for policing campuses that did not match the administration\'92s preferred demographic profile. The moral floor of good faith\'97acting in ways that preserve trust in shared rules\'97was strained as universities were told that dissenting from the government\'92s line on Israel, gender, or race could cost them billions.\
\
Law, which in a healthy democracy limits power, was repeatedly used this week as a weapon. Attorney General Pam Bondi ordered a grand jury investigation into alleged treason by Barack Obama, Hillary Clinton, and other officials over 2016 election interference, reviving long-disputed claims based on \'93Clinton Plan\'94 intelligence that a newly unclassified Durham annex had already undermined. The U.S. Office of Special Counsel opened a Hatch Act probe into former special counsel Jack Smith after Republican complaints that his prosecutions of Trump were political, despite no clear evidence of wrongdoing. At the same time, the Department of Justice issued subpoenas to New York Attorney General Letitia James, whose civil suits had produced a $500 million judgment against Trump and exposed corruption at the NRA. Ed Martin, a partisan figure whose nomination as D.C. U.S. attorney had been withdrawn, was appointed special counsel to investigate whether James\'92s civil cases deprived Trump and Wayne LaPierre of their rights. Legal experts and James\'92s own counsel described the subpoenas as political retribution. The pattern was stark: those who had investigated or prosecuted the president and his allies now found themselves under federal investigation.\
\
In Texas, law and law enforcement were turned against elected legislators. More than fifty Democratic members of the state House left Texas for Illinois and other states to deny a quorum on a mid-decade redistricting plan that would convert five Democratic-leaning congressional districts into Republican ones at Trump\'92s request. Republican leaders responded with a battery of measures: $500 daily fines for absent lawmakers, civil arrest warrants, threats of felony bribery charges for accepting travel support from donors, and petitions to the state supreme court to declare seats vacant and expel leaders like Representative Gene Wu. Governor Greg Abbott ordered state police to arrest the Democrats if they returned, while Senator John Cornyn asked the FBI to help locate and arrest them, and FBI Director Kash Patel reportedly agreed to assist. The FBI has not confirmed specific actions, and no federal warrants were issued, but the signal was clear. Federal law enforcement was being invited into a state political dispute to pressure one party\'92s legislators, blurring the line between criminal investigation and partisan enforcement.\
\
The same logic appeared in Washington, D.C. After an attack on a former Trump official, the president ordered a seven-day federal crackdown on violent crime in the capital, deploying multiple federal agencies to patrol local streets, even as FBI data showed a 26 percent drop in violent crime in D.C. in 2025 and a 35 percent decline the year before. He also threatened to \'93federalize\'94 the city, taking over its governance, despite the absence of a crime wave. The operation was framed as necessary for public safety and could be extended. In practice, it normalized the use of extraordinary federal deployments in a city that had already reduced crime, and it raised fears that homeless people and other vulnerable groups would be targeted under the guise of order. When emergency-style powers are invoked in defiance of the facts, restraint gives way to spectacle, and the law becomes a stage prop rather than a boundary.\
\
Immigration enforcement was the sharpest edge of this carceral turn. ICE announced an expansion of detention capacity by 1,000 beds in Indiana\'92s Miami correctional center, a maximum-security prison, and prepared to open a 5,000-bed facility at Fort Bliss, a military base near El Paso, under a $231.8 million contract with Acquisition Logistics LLC, a company with no prior detention experience. The Fort Bliss site, dubbed Camp East Montana, would be staffed by ICE personnel but built and operated by the contractor under a Department of Defense agreement, with the aim of \'93decompressing\'94 other jails by serving as a processing hub for deportations. In Florida, a new detention center in the Everglades, \'93Alligator Alcatraz,\'94 had already become a symbol of the mass deportation program, holding thousands of people\'97over 70 percent without criminal records\'97in harsh conditions described by a former officer as lacking sunlight, sanitation, and adequate showers. A federal judge, Kathleen Williams, issued a temporary halt on further construction at Alligator Alcatraz, citing potential violations of environmental law and threats to tribal lands, but allowed the facility to keep operating and holding detainees. The ruling showed that courts could still slow, though not stop, the buildout of a vast detention infrastructure.\
\
Reports from Senator Jon Ossoff\'92s office documented more than 500 credible allegations of abuse in ICE facilities since January, including deaths in custody, sexual and physical assaults, mistreatment of pregnant women and children, overcrowding, and denial of access to lawyers. DHS denied the claims, insisting conditions were adequate. At the same time, ICE sought to add 10,000 staff under a megabill that increased its budget by $76.5 billion over four years, launched a media-saturation recruitment campaign targeting Gen Z and former law enforcement, and even briefly floated a pilot program offering cash bonuses to agents who deported migrants within seven days, before rescinding it under backlash. The agency also began recruiting directly from local 287(g) departments, prompting sheriffs to complain that their own forces were being depleted. In Los Angeles, Border Patrol agents conducted \'93Operation Trojan Horse,\'94 an immigration raid outside a Home Depot using an unmarked truck, arresting sixteen people despite a federal court order halting indiscriminate sweeps in the region due to racial profiling. The raid, carried out after an appeals court had upheld the order, suggested that parts of the enforcement apparatus were willing to test or ignore judicial limits.\
\
The security state itself was being reshaped from within. Brian Driscoll, a senior FBI official who had resisted demands to name agents involved in the January 6 investigation and briefly served as acting director, was forced out, along with at least one other agent, in what insiders described as a purge led by Director Kash Patel and Deputy Dan Bongino. The FBI Agents Association warned that such firings undermined the bureau\'92s safety and integrity. At DHS, recruitment messaging adopted language like \'93Serve your country! Defend your culture!\'94 echoing older nationalist propaganda and raising alarms about the ideological profile of new hires. ICE\'92s recruitment campaign sought to flood social media, streaming platforms, and campuses with pro-enforcement imagery, an \'93awareness saturation initiative\'94 designed to dominate the information space. The moral floor of restraint\'97especially in the use of force and surveillance\'97was not only breached but inverted, as agencies were encouraged to see themselves as guardians of a threatened culture rather than neutral enforcers of law.\
\
Representation, the core of democratic legitimacy, was under coordinated pressure. In Texas, the mid-decade redistricting plan, pushed by Trump, aimed to convert five Democratic-leaning congressional districts into Republican ones before the 2026 midterms. In Indiana, Vice President J.D. Vance met with Republican lawmakers to encourage them to redraw their map to secure more GOP seats, even though Republicans already held seven of nine. In Washington, Trump announced that he had ordered the Commerce Department to begin work on a new census that would exclude undocumented immigrants, despite the Constitution\'92s requirement to count \'93whole persons\'94 and prior court rulings blocking similar efforts. Excluding millions from the count would shift House seats and federal funding away from immigrant-heavy states and cities, entrenching minority rule under the banner of \'93fairness.\'94 At the same time, the Supreme Court heard a challenge to Louisiana\'92s remedial map with two majority-Black districts, a case that will determine how far states can go in drawing districts to ensure Black representation without running afoul of equal-protection doctrine. Senator Raphael Warnock and colleagues reintroduced the John R. Lewis Voting Rights Advancement Act to restore federal preclearance and other protections, and some Republicans, like Representative Blake Moore, publicly opposed Texas\'92s mid-decade gerrymander, while Representative Kevin Kiley introduced a bill to ban such mid-cycle redistricting nationwide. These moves showed that the fight over who counts and who chooses is not one-sided, but the weight of executive and state power was clearly on the side of narrowing the electorate.\
