Information and memory were contested fields throughout the week. The White House quietly removed official transcripts of Trump\'92s remarks from public access, limiting the record of what the president had said. Sections of the Constitution Annotated website, including provisions on habeas corpus and foreign emoluments, disappeared due to what the Library of Congress called a coding error, then were restored by day\'92s end. The State Department\'92s draft human-rights reports for El Salvador, Israel, and Russia were leaked, showing softened language and the removal of references to LGBTQ+ people and state abuses, with one draft claiming there were \'93no credible reports of significant human rights abuses\'94 in El Salvador despite prior findings of killings and torture. The administration accepted a $400 million luxury jet from Qatar, raising emoluments concerns and questions about how foreign gifts might shape policy. The Army announced plans to restore a Confederate memorial at Arlington National Cemetery, at a cost of about $10 million, less than two years after its removal, re-centering a symbol of white supremacy and rebellion in the nation\'92s most hallowed military ground. In media, Trump sued the Wall Street Journal\'92s parent company for $10 billion over reporting on his contributions to an Epstein birthday album and sought to depose Rupert Murdoch, a move widely seen as an attempt to intimidate journalists. Meanwhile, major outlets underreported FBI data showing historic declines in crime, even as they gave front-page space to Trump\'92s threats to federalize D.C. over \'93violent crime.\'94 The result was an information environment in which fear and grievance were amplified, while facts that might undercut them were muted.\
\
Higher education, already under financial and regulatory siege, became a central battleground for this struggle over truth and memory. Brown and Columbia\'92s settlements, UCLA\'92s funding freeze, Harvard\'92s lawsuits, and the admissions-data orders all pointed in the same direction: universities would be allowed to function only if they accepted the administration\'92s definitions of antisemitism, gender, and merit, and if they policed student and faculty speech accordingly. A medical student at Emory sued the university over its treatment of activism related to Israel and Gaza, invoking federal anti-discrimination laws to challenge how institutions balance free speech and harassment claims. These cases showed that universities were not only being disciplined from above but also pulled into court from below, with the federal government often taking sides in ways that favored its own ideological allies. The moral floor of truthfulness\'97protecting spaces where evidence and argument can be weighed without fear\'97was eroded as campuses were told that their survival depended on aligning with the state\'92s story.\
\
Amid this, there were still signs of institutional resistance and civic courage. The federal judge\'92s order halting further construction at Alligator Alcatraz, even for just two weeks, showed that environmental law and tribal claims could still slow executive projects. The coalition lawsuit against EPA\'92s termination of the Environmental and Climate Justice grant program invoked the separation of powers, arguing that the agency could not simply ignore a congressional mandate. Democracy Forward\'92s suit for Epstein records, Radar Online\'92s FOIA litigation, and the House Oversight Committee\'92s subpoenas for Epstein files and testimony from former officials all sought to pierce the veil of secrecy around elite crimes. Texas Democrats\'92 walkout, Indiana protests against redistricting, and town-hall chants of \'93Vote him out!\'94 in Nebraska showed that citizens and legislators were willing to use the tools still available to them, even at personal risk, as when a bomb threat forced Texas lawmakers to evacuate their Illinois hotel. These acts did not yet change the structural balance of power, but they kept alive the habits of dissent and oversight that any future repair will require.\
\
Looking ahead from Week 29, several scheduled or ongoing processes bear close watching. The Supreme Court\'92s decision on Louisiana\'92s map will set a precedent for how race can be used to secure minority representation in redistricting. The implementation of Trump\'92s new tariffs, including the 25 percent duty on Indian imports and the threatened 100 percent tariffs on semiconductors and Spanish goods, will test both economic resilience and diplomatic ties. The Department of Commerce\'92s work on a census that excludes undocumented immigrants, if it proceeds, will likely face immediate legal challenges that will clarify how firmly the constitutional requirement to count all persons still stands. The expansion of ICE facilities at Fort Bliss and in Indiana, and the outcome of lawsuits over Alligator Alcatraz and the canceled Environmental and Climate Justice grants, will show whether courts can still constrain the growth of a profit-driven detention state. In higher education, Harvard\'92s lawsuits, the independent monitors at Columbia, and the admissions-data demands will determine how much autonomy universities retain in the face of federal pressure.\
\
The Democracy Clock remains at 7:57 p.m. at the close of this week, but the stillness of the hands should not be mistaken for safety. What Week 29 reveals is not a sudden lurch toward midnight, but the steady normalization of practices that, taken together, hollow out the moral floor on which democratic life rests. Executive orders reach into ever more domains, from homelessness to retirement savings to university curricula, with little effective oversight. Law is aimed at opponents and shields allies, while those who once enforced it impartially are purged or investigated. Security forces are expanded, militarized, and recruited with culture-war rhetoric, and their deployments are justified by narratives that defy the government\'92s own data. Economic policy is written to serve donors and insiders, even as millions lose food assistance and face higher prices. Information and memory are curated by power, with inconvenient facts buried, archives altered, and monuments to conquest restored.\
\
Yet the week also shows that the story is not finished. Courts still issue injunctions. Legislators still walk out. Citizens still protest, sue, and vote. Universities still go to court to defend their independence. The Civic Covenant, as the moral-floor analysis suggests, has largely cracked across character, ethics, restraint, truthfulness, good faith, and stewardship, but it has not vanished. The task for future weeks, and for those who will read this record in classrooms and courts, is to see how close the country came to accepting these breaches as normal, and how much effort it will take to rebuild the habits and structures that once made them unthinkable. For now, the official time at the end of Week 29 remains 7:57 p.m. The hour is late, but the clock has not yet struck.\
